Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/ParliamentarySittingDayType
Object: COMBINED COMMENT FROM OLD CLASSES: A sitting day in a House is a day during which that House considers business, with Members being quorate in the Chamber of that House and in the presence of the Mace. The Mace signifies the Monarch as a component part of Parliament. Sitting days are determined by each House separately. Parliament considers that a sitting day may continue beyond midnight to include more than one calendar day: such a sitting day is called by the date of the calendar day on which it begins. Except in the case of the European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018, Sch. 7 para. 17(11), which uses the above definition, legislation assumes one calendar day to be one sitting day. ///// A hybrid sitting day in a House is a day during which that House considers business, with a quorum of Members, including both those present in the Chamber and those attending remotely, and in the presence of the Mace. Hybrid sitting days are determined by each House separately. Parliament considers that a hybrid sitting day may continue beyond midnight to include more than one calendar day: such a hybrid sitting day is called by the date of the calendar day on which it begins. //// A virtual sitting day in a House is a day during which that House considers business with a quorum of Members attending remotely, without the presence of the Mace. During a virtual sitting day, a House can conduct a debate but cannot put a question for decision. Questions are put to the House when not sitting virtually.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/adjournmentDayInHouse
Object: Relates an adjournment day to the House in which that adjournment day takes place.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/isBillOfficeTablingDay
Object: MUNGED: Used to record if an adjournment day is a Bill Office tabling day. A day other than a sitting day on which a Member of a House may give notice of an amendment, new clause or new schedule to a Bill to the Public Bill Office of that House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/isTableOfficeTablingDay
Object: MUNGED: Used to record if an adjournment day is a Table Office tabling day. A day other than a sitting day on which a Member of a House may give notice of a question, motion or amendment to a motion to the Table Office of that House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasParliamentarySittingDayType
Object: Relates a parliamentary sitting day to its type.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/adjournmentDayInSession
Object: Relates an adjournment day to the session in which that adjournment day takes place.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/ProrogationPeriod
Object: The time period between a prorogation and either dissolution or the start of the subsequent session. A prorogation period is within a Parliament period. Parliamentary business does not take place during a prorogation period. A prorogation period is the same across both Houses. A proclamation to prorogue Parliament is made under a prerogative power of the Crown.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/prorogationInParliamentPeriod
Object: Relates a prorogation period to the Parliament period in which that prorogation period takes place.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/sessionInParliamentPeriod
Object: Relates a session to the Parliament period in which that session takes place.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/parliamentPeriodInKingdom
Object: Relates a Parliament period to the kingdom in which that Parliament period takes place.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/Recess
Object: A 'periodic adjournment' during a session, when one or both Houses have adjourned to a day other than the next expected sitting day. A periodic adjournment ends with prorogation, dissolution or a new term.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/dissolutionPeriodInKingdom
Object: Relates a dissolution period to the kingdom in which that dissolution period takes place.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/groupedInto
Object: Relates an adjournment day to the recess of which it forms part.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/postElectionDissolutionPeriodInDissolutionPeriod
Object: Post-election dissolution period in dissolution period

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/isDraftLayingDay
Object: Used to record if an adjournment day is a day on which draft instruments may be laid.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/AdjournmentDay
Object: A day on which a House is adjourned, for example: a 'non-sitting Friday', a day on a weekend, a Bank Holiday.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/parliamentarySittingDayInSession
Object: Relates a parliamentary sitting day to the session in which that parliamentary sitting day takes place.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/PostElectionDissolutionPeriod
Object: The period between the results of all constituency elections being announced and the next Parliament period. During this period, successful candidates are Members even though Parliament is dissolved.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/TemporalThing
Object: An interval between two points in time, having a name.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/PreElectionDissolutionPeriod
Object: The period between the end of a Parliament period and the results of all constituency elections being announced. During this time there are no Members of the House of Commons.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/Session
Object: A period during which Parliament is able to conduct business on days of its choosing. A session is within a Parliament period. The first session of a Parliament begins on the same day as the Parliament period and ends on a day named in a subsequent prorogation proclamation. Subsequent sessions within the Parliament period begin and end on dates named in subsequent prorogation proclamations. The final session of a Parliament ends either with prorogation followed by dissolution or with dissolution. Session periods are the same for both Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/postElectionDissolutionPeriodInDissolutionPeriod
Object: Relates a post-election dissolution period to the dissolution period of which that post-election dissolution period is part.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/preElectionDissolutionPeriodInDissolutionPeriod
Object: Pre-election dissolution period in dissolution period

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/parliamentarySittingDayInHouse
Object: Relates a parliamentary sitting day to the House in which that parliamentary sitting day takes place.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/Reign
Object: A period of time during which a monarch has a reign in a kingdom.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/Kingdom
Object: A Kingdom is a period of time between the establishment of a Kingdom and the disestablishment of that Kingdom, for example: the United Kingdom existing from 1st January 1801.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-point/
Object: A model describing time periods used by the UK Parliament.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/preElectionDissolutionPeriodInDissolutionPeriod
Object: Relates a pre-election dissolution period to the dissolution period of which that pre-election dissolution period is part.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/PremiershipPeriod
Object: A continuous period of government under a single Prime Minister, spanning general elections, for example: Thatcher administration 1979-1990.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/GovernmentAdministrationPeriod
Object: A period of a single government, under a single Prime Minister, bounded by general elections, for example: Thatcher administration 1979-1983, Thatcher administration 1983-1987, Thatcher administration 1987-1990.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/isPrintingDay
Object: MUNGED: Used to record if an adjournment day is a printing day. In the House of Commons, a printing day is the day on which the Table Office publishes notices of questions, motions and amendments to motions received since the most recent sitting day. A printing day falls on the same day as the final weekday of a recess other than a bank holiday.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/House
Object: A parliamentary House, for example: the House of Lords.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/DissolutionPeriod
Object: The period during which Parliament is dissolved. During this time no parliamentary business can take place. From the time of dissolution until the returning of a result for a constituency in a general election, that constituency has no Member sitting in the House of Commons. Winners returned for a constituency in a general election are Members from the time of being returned, even if Parliament is dissolved. Members of the House of Lords retain their memberships during a dissolution period. A dissolution period applies to both Houses. A proclamation to dissolve Parliament is made under a prerogative power of the Crown.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/ParliamentPeriod
Object: The time period of a single Parliament between the date of its first assembly after a general election and its dissolution. A Parliament period contains contiguous session and prorogation periods. During a parliament period Parliament is either in session or prorogued. The start date of a Parliament may be changed by subsequent proclamations. A Parliament ends at the next dissolution. While the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 was in force, the date of dissolution was determined by that Act or was named in a proclamation following a vote in Parliament for an early general election. The next Parliament began on the date named in the proclamation issued following a dissolution. Before the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 came into force and after that Act was repealed by the Dissolution and Calling of Parliament Act 2022, the date of dissolution is fixed by proclamation. The dissolution proclamation also names the date for Parliament to reassemble. Parliament periods are the same across both Houses. Parliaments are numbered ordinally from the first Parliament of the United Kingdom, sitting in 1801.
